In article <Ct29Av.C78@adl33cc.adelphi.edu>, cr9825g92@auvax1.adelphi.edu writes:
|> I have read the FAQ on public key encryption and am wondering, why can't the 
|> public key encryption algorithm be reversed.
|> ie. for RSA e_k(p) = p^e mod pq, d_k(c) = c^d mod pq
|> There is no mathematical way to reverse the function e_k(p)
|> ???

Sure there is. The problem is that you don't know p and q when you encrypt.
You only know n. In order to figure out d and invert e_k(p) you need p and q
(because e is the multiplicative inverse of d in mod ((p-1)*(q-1)). Finding p
and q without n takes a LONG time for a 1024 bit n.

JWS
